# Service Handler Convention

Apply this convention for runtime code, especially `services/**/*.ts`.

## Layering

- Keep `handler.ts` as a thin Lambda entry file only.
- Put runtime orchestration logic in same-folder `index.ts`.
- Move non-trivial business flow from `index.ts` into `usecase/`.
- Keep external I/O in `repo/` (AWS SDK, DynamoDB, S3, HTTP providers).
- Isolate external provider calls in `services/shared/lib/providers/<provider>/*.ts`.
- Keep data shape conversion in `mapper/` and normalization in `normalize/`.

## Handler Rules

- `handler.ts` should only wire and delegate: `export const handler = run`.
- No direct provider calls in `handler.ts`.
- No JSON schema/business validation logic in `handler.ts`.
- No direct external API calls in `index.ts`; call `usecase` or provider modules.
- Avoid inline status transitions in `handler.ts`; delegate to called function.
- For `services/admin/**/index.ts`, default to `runAuditedAdminResolver(...)`.
- Use `resolver-audit-fields` helpers for audit metadata instead of inline result casts or path reads.

## Naming

- Entry orchestrator: `run` in `index.ts`.
- Usecase functions: verb-first names (e.g. `generateSceneAssets`).
- Repo functions: boundary-first names (e.g. `putSceneAsset`, `getJobMeta`).

## Quality Gates

- Preserve event contracts and response shape when refactoring.
- Prefer pure functions for normalization/mapping blocks.
- Keep files single-purpose and easy to test in isolation.
- Use named exports only; avoid default exports in `services/**`.
- After the second repetition of a field flow, promote it to `services/<domain>/shared/*`.
- If a usecase copies 5+ fields into a payload or branches by 3+ sibling cases, extract `mapper/`, `repo/`, or `policies/`.
